04920nam a22007575i 9780271032399DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212005pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710323997 a10.1515/97802710323992doi  a(DE-B1597)584029  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0090002bisacsh04a305.42098662221 aLind, Amy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGendered Paradoxes :bWomen's Movements, State Restructuring, and Global Development in Ecuador /cAmy Lind. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE AND ACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tList of acronyms -- tIntroduction -- t1 Myths of Progress: Citizenship, Modernization, and Women's Rights Struggles in Ecuador -- t2 Ecuadorian Neoliberalisms and Gender Politics in Context -- t3 Neoliberal Encounters: State Restructuring and the Institutionalization of Women's Struggles for Survival -- t4 Women's Community Organizing in Quito: The Paradoxes of Survival and Struggle -- t5 Remaking the Nation: Feminist Politics, Populist Nationalism, and the 1998 Constitutional Reforms -- t6 Making Dollars, Making Feminist Sense of Neoliberalism: Negotiations, Paradoxes, Futures -- tAppendix: Chronology of Events -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the early 1980s Ecuador has experienced a series of events unparalleled in its history. Its "free market" strategies exacerbated the debt crisis, and in response new forms of social movement organizing arose among the country's poor, including women's groups. Gendered Paradoxes focuses on women's participation in the political and economic restructuring process of the past twenty-five years, showing how in their daily struggle for survival Ecuadorian women have both reinforced and embraced the neoliberal model yet also challenged its exclusionary nature. Drawing on her extensive ethnographic fieldwork and employing an approach combining political economy and cultural politics, Amy Lind charts the growth of several strands of women's activism and identifies how they have helped redefine, often in contradictory ways, the real and imagined boundaries of neoliberal development discourse and practice. In her analysis of this ambivalent and "unfinished" cultural project of modernity in the Andes, she examines state policies and their effects on women of various social sectors; women's community development initiatives and responses to the debt crisis; and the roles played by feminist "issue networks" in reshaping national and international policy agendas in Ecuador and in developing a transnationally influenced, locally based feminist movement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aFeminismxEcuador. 0aFeminismzEcuador. 0aIndian womenxEcuador. 0aIndian womenzEcuador. 0aPoor womenxEcuador. 0aPoor womenzEcuador. 0aStructural adjustment (Economic policy)xEcuador. 0aStructural adjustment (Economic policy)zEcuador. 0aWomen in developmentxEcuador. 0aWomen in developmentzEcuador. 0aWomenxPolitical activityxEcuador. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzEcuador. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271032399zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271032399423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271032399.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEB